{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486741"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"166"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582458"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"166"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/166"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.03,0.11,0.11,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91646"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/166"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75216"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31292"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91646"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman is being followed up after resection of a T3 N1 M0 carcinoma of the colon. In the first few years of follow-up she will require regular CT and colonoscopic examinations. In addition, tumour marker studies would also be appropriate to monitor her response to treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Measurement of which one of the following tumour markers would be most appropriate to monitor her response to treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alpha-fetoprotein","Cancer Antigen 15-3","Cancer Antigen 19-9","Cancer antigen 125","Carcinoembryonic antigen"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoembryonic antigen\u003C/strong\u003E (CEA) is a tumour marker commonly elevated in colorectal cancer patients. It is useful for monitoring response to treatment and detecting recurrence in patients with colon cancer. It is the most appropriate option for monitoring response to treatment in this scenario. This tumour marker may also be elevated in gastric, hepatic, lung, pancreatic, ovarian and prostate adenocarcinoma. It may be high in a few benign conditions like inflammatory bowel disease, pancreatitis and in smokers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-fetoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E (AFP) is a glycoprotein produced by the foetal liver, yolk sac, and gastrointestinal tract during embryonic development. In adults, elevated AFP levels are primarily indicative of hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), a type of liver cancer. AFP levels can also be elevated in certain germ cell tumours, such as yolk sac tumours and embryonal carcinomas. AFP is utilized as a tumour marker in diagnosing, prognosis, and monitoring HCC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003ECancer Antigen 15-3\u003C/strong\u003E (CA 15-3) is primarily associated with breast cancer, especially in advanced stages or metastatic disease. Certain benign breast conditions such as fibrocystic changes or benign breast tumours may also result in elevated CA 15-3 levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003ECancer Antigen 19-9\u003C/strong\u003E (CA 19-9) is elevated in various gastrointestinal cancers, including pancreatic, gallbladder, biliary tract, oesophagus and gastric cancers. It is mainly used for monitoring pancreatic and biliary cancer. It may also be elevated in benign conditions like choledocholithiasis, acute and chronic pancreatitis, diverticulitis, Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis, and rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003ECancer Antigen 125\u003C/strong\u003E (CA 125) is primarily used as a tumour marker for ovarian cancer. Also, this may be elevated in other malignancies (uterus, breast, lung, oesophagus, gastric, hepatic and pancreatic cancers) and benign conditions (pelvic inflammatory disease, peritonitis, ascites, pericarditis and pleural effusion).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tumour marker studies should be used in conjunction with other modalities in the follow-up of colorectal cancer patients."],"references":["Nicholson, BD, Shinkins, B, Pathiraja, I, Roberts, NW, James, TJ, Mallett, S, Perera, R, Primrose, JN \u0026 Mant, D 2015, \u2018Blood CEA levels for detecting recurrent colorectal cancer\u2019, Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews, no. 12.","Mariampillai AI, Cruz JPD, Suh J, Sivapiragasam A, Nevins K, Hindenburg AA. Cancer Antigen 72-4 for the Monitoring of Advanced Tumors of the Gastrointestinal Tract, Lung, Breast and Ovaries. Anticancer Res. 2017 Jul;37(7):3649-3656. doi: 10.21873/anticanres.11735. PMID: 28668856.","Adigun OO, Yarrarapu SNS, Zubair M, et al. Alpha Fetoprotein. [Updated 2023 Jan 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430750/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75216"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"166"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75216"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T07:57:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-16T07:57:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"166"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91646"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"385","links":{"self":"https://a